"obj": "gene", "prob": 0.921428918838501, "span": {"begin": 660, "end": 667}}, {"id": ["mesh:C002491"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "WIN18,466", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9993078112602234, "span": {"begin": 672, "end": 681}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014212"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "atRA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9973642230033875, "span": {"begin": 701, "end": 705}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10095"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mice", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9902312159538269, "span": {"begin": 771, "end": 775}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9986"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "rabbits", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9558965563774109, "span": {"begin": 777, "end": 784}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:7955"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "zebrafish", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9268330931663513, "span": {"begin": 789, "end": 798}}], "text": "The empirical evidence for linkage is strong and widely accepted. The enzymatic activity of ALDH1A2 and capacity to oxidize retinal has been proven in vitro (see KE 1880). In vivo, the strongest evidence comes from the Aldh1a2-deficient mice that fail to synthesize retinoic acid during embryogenesis (Niederreither et al, 1999). Additionally, ovary culture with the potent ALDH1A2 inhibitor WIN18,446 results in failure to upregulate the atRA-regulated gene Stra8 in oocytes, resulting in germ cell loss (Rosario et al, 2020). Additional evidence for this relationship using WIN18,466 also comes from in vivo studies looking at spermatogenesis; inhibition of ALDH1A2 via WIN18,466 results in loss of atRA expression and halted spermatogenesis in diverse species such as mice, rabbits and zebrafish (Amory et al, 2011; Paik et al, 2014; Pradhan &amp; Olsson, 2015).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:35:10 +0000 2026"}